\f1\b0\fs42 \cf0 Combine the orange juice, grapefruit juice, lemon juice, lime juice, and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.foodterms.com/encyclopedia/vodka/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 vodka}}, if using, in a pitcher. Dip the rim of 6 {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.foodterms.com/encyclopedia/martini/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 martini}} glasses first in a dish with lemon juice and then a dish with {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.foodterms.com/encyclopedia/sugar/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 sugar}}. Set aside to dry.\
When ready to serve, place ice cubes in a cocktail shaker, add the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.foodterms.com/encyclopedia/cocktail/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 cocktail}} mixture to fill the shaker 3/4 full, and shake for about 30 seconds. It's important to shake for a full 30 seconds to get the drink very cold and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.foodterms.com/encyclopedia/dilute/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 dilute}} it slightly with the ice. Pour into the sugared martini glasses and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.foodterms.com/encyclopedia/garnish/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 garnish}} with a sprig of mint. Continue filling the shaker with ice and cocktail mixture until all the drinks are poured. Serve ice cold.}